The '''Findern Manuscript''' (CUL MS Ff.1.6) is a paper codex written entirely in [[Middle English]] and compiled in the fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries by a series of [[gentry]] who were neighbors in the countryside of [[Derbyshire]]. A list of its major texts creates a “greatest hits” of fourteenth-century secular love literature; however the volume also contains around two dozen anonymous lyrics, which have been added in the blank spaces left at the bottoms of pages and the ends of quires. There are several names and scribal signatures written into the book, including the names of five women.<ref>{{cite book|last=Beadle|first=Richard|title=The Findern Manuscript: Cambridge University Library MS CUL Ff.1.6|year=1977|publisher=The Scholars Press|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Harris|first=Kate|title=The Origins and Make-up of Cambridge University Library Ms Ff.1.6|journal=Transactions of the Cambridge Bibliographical Society|year=1983|volume=8|issue=3|pages=299–333}}</ref>
