{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox UN resolution | number = 502 | organ = SC | image = Falkland Islands topographic map-en.svg | caption = Map of the Falkland Islands | date = 3 April | year = 1982 | meeting = 2,350 | code = S/RES/502 | document = https://undocs.org/S/RES/502(1982) | subject = {{nowrap|Falkland Islands {{smaller|{{nobold|(''Malvinas'')}}}}}} | for=10 | against = 1 | abstention = 4 | result = Adopted }}
'''United Nations Security Council Resolution 502''' was a resolution adopted by the [[United Nations Security Council]] on 3 April 1982. After expressing its concern at [[1982 invasion of the Falkland Islands|the invasion of]] the [[Falkland Islands]] by the [[Armed Forces of the Argentine Republic|armed forces]] of Argentina, the Council demanded an immediate cessation of hostilities between Argentina and the United Kingdom and a complete withdrawal by Argentine forces. The Council also called on the governments of Argentina and the United Kingdom to seek a diplomatic solution to the situation and refrain from further military action.
The resolution, tabled by the British representative, Amb. [[Anthony Parsons|Sir Anthony Parsons]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1899334.stm |title=Falklands War: The first day, 2 April 1982 |date=2 April 2002 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> was adopted by 10 votes to 1 against (Panama) with four [[abstention]]s (China, Poland, Spain and the Soviet Union).
Resolution 502, which was in the United Kingdom's favour, gave the UK the option to invoke [[Chapter VII of the United Nations Charter#Article 51|Article 51 of the United Nations Charter]] and claim the [[Self-defence_in_international_law|right of self-defence]]. It was supported by members of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] and by the [[European Economic Community]], which later imposed sanctions on Argentina.<ref>{{cite book |last=Gibran |first=Daniel K. |title=The Falklands War: Britain Versus the Past in the South Atlantic |publisher=McFarland |date=2007 |pages=77 |isbn=978-0-7864-3736-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ChMhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QXUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1755,5144126&dq= |title=The legalities of the Falkland Islands crisis |last=Maechling Jr |first=Charles |date=27 April 1982 |work=The Day}}</ref>
